The paper discusses a computing system based on population coding with magnetic tunnel junctions that implement both neurons and synaptic weights. This system is designed to be robust to the unreliability of its constituent nanodevices, which suggests that it falls under the category of "Neural and Evolutionary Computing" (cs.NE). Additionally, the use of magnetic tunnel junctions implies that the paper may also fall under the categories of "Emerging Technologies" (cs.ET) and "Electromagnetics" (cs.EM). The paper also discusses the use of continuous learning to overcome device unreliability, which suggests that it may fall under the category of "Artificial Intelligence" (cs.AR). Finally, the paper discusses the trade-off between power consumption and precision, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of "Mathematical Physics" (cs.MA).
